instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "Control signals such as steering angle, throttle level, and servo positions are produced by the Virtual Cockpit UI and sent as ROS2 action messages over the local middleware to the Actuation FE. The Actuation FE validates the command payload (ensuring correct format and acceptable ranges) before transmitting it to the vehicle’s on‑board control system via a UDP socket over the same Wi‑Fi link used for sensor data. The on‑board system replies with a simple ACK containing the sequence identifier, which the Actuation FE forwards to the virtual twin to close the feedback loop."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin synchronizes the virtual and physical subsystems to a shared notion of time with a maximum relative deviation of 100 ms. This 100 ms accuracy is mandated by hardware constraints and meets the stricter synchronization thresholds of safety‑critical vehicular standards. All ROS2 messages and sensor data timestamps are aligned to this accuracy, ensuring that time granularity for critical safety services is 100 ms and that end‑to‑end latency from sensor acquisition to actuation remains below this bound."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin is orchestrated following ISO 23247 RA, mapping each software component to a Functional Entity (FE). Each FE is implemented as a dedicated ROS2 package containing one or more ROS2 nodes. The User Interface FE is split into two sub‑components—3D Visualization and Control Panel—both instantiated within the User Entity. Data management, control logic and pre‑processing reside in the Digital Twin Entity, while actuation and sensor interfacing are handled by the Physical Twin Entity. Inter‑entity communication is performed over ROS2 publish‑subscribe and client‑server topics, ensuring resource allocation, component integration, and system‑wide coordination across the distributed hardware deployment."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "All intra‑software component communication is implemented atop ROS2 using the Data‑Distribution Service (DDS) over UDP. Inter‑entity connections between the vehicle and the Digital Twin server are established over a Wi‑Fi 802.11n network using UDP sockets. Each message includes a sequence number and checksum to guarantee ordering and data integrity. The network topology is a flat, distributed structure with no dedicated encryption or VPN layers specified in the source document."
]

instance data_ownership_and_privacy : DTDFVocab:DataOwnershipPrivacy [
    base:desc "The 3GPP TS 22.185 service‑requirements specification for vehicle‑to‑everything (V2X) communications mandates compliance with the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR). It requires explicit user consent before any personal data is shared, mandates pseudonymisation or anonymisation of identifiers in vehicular messages, enforces data‑minimisation limits, and defines data‑sharing agreements between mobile and roadside infrastructures. Encryption of V2X traffic must use TLS 1.3 or an equivalent PKI‑based scheme, and TLS certificates must be signed by a trusted certificate authority as part of the authentication and access‑control mechanisms. The spec also recommends periodic data‑retention reviews and deletion of data after the necessary lifecycle for safety analytics, ensuring that any aggregated data used for digital‑twin model training is anonymised and stored in a secure, role‑based access environment."
]

